Socket <I=5>

Description 

Creates a TCP/IP connection, or establishes a TCP/IP server.

Properties 

  ---------------------------------- ---------------------------------------------------------------------
  <L=4O#2> connected </L> readonly   When true, the connection is active.

  <L=4P#2> encoding </L> readonly    Sets or retrieves the name of the encoding used to transmit data.

  <L=4Q#2> eof </L> readonly         When true, the receive buffer is empty.

  <L=4R#2> error </L> readonly       A message describing the most recent error. Setting this value clears
                                     any error message.

  <L=4S#2> host </L> readonly        The name of the remote computer when a connection is established.

  <L=4Y#2> timeout </L> readonly     The timeout in seconds to be applied to read or write operations.
  ---------------------------------- ---------------------------------------------------------------------

Constructors 

  ----------------------------------------------------------- --------------------------------------------
  <L=4M#2> Socket </L> readonly                               Creates a new Socket object.

  ----------------------------------------------------------- --------------------------------------------

Methods 

  ----------------------- --------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  <L=4N#2> close </L>     Terminates the open connection.
  readonly                

  <L=4T#3> listen </L>    Instructs the object to start listening for an incoming connection.
  readonly                

  <L=4U#3> open </L>      Opens the connection for subsequent read/write operations.
  readonly                

  <L=4V#2> poll </L>      Checks a listening object for a new incoming connection.
  readonly                

  <L=4W#3> read </L>      Reads up to the specified number of characters from the connection. CR
  readonly                characters are ignored unless the encoding is set to “BINARY”.

  <L=4X#2> readln </L>    Reads one line of text up to the next line feed.
  readonly                

  <L=4Z#3> write </L>     Concatenates all arguments into a single string and writes that string to the
  readonly                connection.

  <L=50#3> writeln </L>   Concatenates all arguments into a single string, appends a LF character, and
  readonly                writes that string to the connection.
  ----------------------- --------------------------------------------------------------------------------

